5_0	0.0	SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y.
5_1	0.2857142857142857	_ The road leading into the Shinnecock Indian reservation is not a welcoming one: The sign marking the way reads, ``Trespassers will be arrested''.
5_2	0.08333333333333333	Some uninvited people _ drug dealers and government workers _ have been reportedly fired upon after crossing onto tribal lands.
5_3	0.0	Tourists are simply asked to leave.
5_4	0.25	The Indians are an insular lot.
5_5	0.0	The world outside their 800-acre reservation here on the Shinnecock Peninsula knows little about them, and for 350 years, that's the way they have preferred it.
5_6	0.0	Their dealings with society, they say, have never been good.
5_7	0.0	``It seems every time we've dealt with the white man, we've come out the worse for it,'' said Harriet Gumbs, a 79-year-old elder and a tribal historian.
5_8	0.0	The reservation is a postage stamp of marshland swamped by poverty and unemployment.
5_9	0.0	For years, the Indians watched as land that was once theirs was transformed into housing subdivisions.
5_10	0.0	Although they complained, there were few sympathetic ears at the local courthouse and Town Hall.
5_11	0.0	After all, they had signed treaties and land-swap agreements, officials say.
5_12	0.0	``They built on our ancestors' bones, and we never really did anything to stop it,'' said Elizabeth Haile, 69, a member of the Thunderbird clan who watched over the years as houses and other buildings sprouted up around the reservation.
5_13	0.0	``That's changing with the young people''.
5_14	0.0	East End power brokers on Long Island have taken notice as this new breed of Shinnecock have lain in front of bulldozers, marched on Town Hall and protested on the steps of the state Capitol in Albany to stop the development of 62 acres of virgin woodland to the north of the Montauk Highway, the road that separates the reservation from the rest of Southampton.
5_15	0.0	The news of the protests has spread from Indian-run radio in Canada to the editorial pages of The News From Indian Country, a newspaper.
5_16	0.1111111111111111	The young Shinnecock have been radicalized by the success of tribes that were once destitute, like the Oneida Indians.
5_17	0.0	The Oneida reservation was once a tumble-down 32 acres in upstate New York, but the tribe now owns the state's largest casino and has a land claim wending its way through federal court asking for the return of 250,000 acres between Syracuse and Utica.
5_18	0.0	As a result, the young group of Shinnecock are talking aggressively about claiming 3,600 acres of prime Southampton real estate that includes three golf courses _ among them the renowned Shinnecock Hills, site of the U.S.
