5_30	0.058823529411764705	The Indians have stopped short of laying formal claim to the 62 acres, but say the wooded site is a small but sacred portion of their heritage that should be preserved.
5_31	0.3	The Shinnecock are a state-recognized tribe, but one of more than 100 Indian tribes not acknowledged by the federal government.
5_32	0.1111111111111111	They have no access to federal education and health money and run no gambling operations.
5_33	0.16666666666666666	More important, they receive no legal assistance from the Bureau of Indian Affairs, so their land claims hang in limbo.
5_34	0.0	According to records, in the early 18th century, the town of Southampton paid the tribe $20 for its land and gave it a 1,000-year lease on the 3,600 acres.
5_35	0.0	In 1859, town officials convinced the state legislature that the Shinnecock were willing to break that lease to allow the Long Island Rail Road to go through in exchange for outright title to the current reservation on Shinnecock Neck.
