8_0	0.0	CROW AGENCY, Mont.
8_1	0.0	_ First the Crow were bullied by the Sioux from these red cliffs and rolling yellow hills of buffalo grass.
8_2	0.0	Later they struck an alliance with the United States and fell here alongside Custer.
8_3	0.0	In time, Washington force-fed treaties to the Crow, bunching them on the reservation while inviting in white settlers as models of how to run a store or farm the land.
8_4	0.0	Prosperity has yet to reach the undulating horizon of south-central Montana's Indian country, but the Crow have caught on to that most loathed of European imports _ the tax.
8_5	0.0	Aimed at the tourist trade, a tribe-levied surcharge sets white fishing guides, shopkeepers and service station owners to griping about taxation without representation.
8_6	0.0625	To those whites who feel unwelcome on the 2.5 million-acre reservation, who feel officially less than Indians living under the same huge sky, the Crow say tough.
8_7	0.0	``If you don't like it,'' said Carl Venne, the Crow's director of public safety, ``then get the hell out of here''.
8_8	0.0	Like the Crow, tribes throughout the country move with new resolve to exercise an old asset: sovereignty.
8_9	0.0	It is that dominion that makes them not just another census category, but hundreds of nations within a nation.
8_10	0.0	This peculiar status stems from a time when Indians controlled more than three-fourths of what would become the United States, prompting the writers of the Constitution to place tribes on an equal footing with foreign nations.
8_11	0.0	The ``white fathers'' in Washington underlined that status in 371 treaties that followed.
8_12	0.0	Since 1830 the Supreme Court has affirmed that although tribes are domestic and dependent, they are still part of an American family of governments entitled to self-rule.
8_13	0.5238095238095238	That sovereignty opens the way for casinos, guarantees American Indians extraordinary fishing and hunting rights, allows them to sell gasoline and cigarettes on Indian territory free of state taxes.
8_14	0.0	Those Indians-only enterprises, in turn, give new resources to some of the poorest Americans in the United States.
8_15	0.0	That money also serves as life support for hundreds of dying languages and offers a sliver of hope for the survival of customs overwhelmed by European-bred culture.
8_16	0.0	Yet the show of treaty-backed authority cues wails of protest from non-Indians.
8_17	0.05555555555555555	``I can't participate in their government,'' said Gordon Rose, a former lawyer who runs an outfitters shop and a small group of cabins near the Bighorn River.
8_18	0.0	The Crow have put a lien on his business for not paying the sales tax they first imposed in 1995.
8_19	0.0	``Why should I be subject to their control''?
8_20	0.0	That argument, say tribes, overlooks history and the law.
8_21	0.0	``You hear people talking about special rights that are anachronistic or ancient,'' said Steven Tullberg, who directs the Washington, D.C., office of the Indian Law Resource Center, based in Helena, Mont.
8_22	0.0	``Most of those rights are younger than our Constitution.
8_23	0.0	We don't disparage the Constitution by saying it's ancient''.
8_24	0.08333333333333333	Assigning different rights to one group based on bloodlines may seem anomalous in this republic born of a declaration that ``all men are created equal''.
8_25	0.3	But sovereignty clearly means recognizing Indians as not only Native Americans but also as special Americans.
8_26	0.6153846153846154	Indians working on reservations avoid state income taxes but pay federal income and Social Security taxes.
8_27	0.6428571428571429	They can vote in local, state and federal elections _ a right that didn't exist for them in New Mexico, for instance, until 1948.
8_28	0.0	But a non-Indian resident of a reservation has no say in tribal government.
8_29	0.09090909090909091	An Indian who commits a crime outside a reservation is destined for the usual federal, state or local courts.
8_30	0.2727272727272727	Indian authorities deal with tribal members for minor crimes on reservations but turn to the FBI or the U.S.
8_31	0.2	Bureau of Indian Affairs police to deal with murders, armed robberies or organized crime.
8_32	0.0	That can get confusing when, for instance, a non-Indian is burglarized on a reservation.
8_33	0.0	If the burglar is a member of the tribe, then tribal police handle the case.
8_34	0.0	If the burglar is white, then a county sheriff might step in.
8_35	0.0	But who's in charge until you catch the thief?
8_36	0.0	It isn't always clear, either, what constitutes Indian country.
8_37	0.0	Treaties dating sometimes to the 18th century often contradict each other.
8_38	0.2727272727272727	But on land that is theirs, tribes can decide whether to set zoning, to ban alcohol or to open casinos.
8_39	0.0	``Without (reservations), and the claim to separate government they represent, Indians would, for all practical purposes, be no different from other ethnic minorities in the United States,'' wrote Fergus Bordewich in ``Killing the White Man's Indian''.
8_40	0.4	Along with granting tribes self-rule and reserving them land, the federal government still pays for vast territory taken from tribes with a promise of sustenance.
8_41	0.2222222222222222	Mostly that takes the form of services _ clinics, schools, welfare _ like those provided to poor people elsewhere.
8_42	0.3333333333333333	Some tribes, such as the Cherokee in Oklahoma, have worked to wean themselves from federal dependency as funding for Indian programs has waned.
8_43	0.0	The Cherokee, for instance, generate more than half their tribal income from enterprises that include a ranch, a lumber company and several plants that manufacture wire for corporations and the military.
8_44	0.13636363636363635	``Sometimes I really feel discouraged when I imagine our ancestors hearing us saying that we can't live without the (Bureau of Indian Affairs),'' said then-Cherokee Chief Wilma Mankiller to other Indian leaders in 1992.
8_45	0.0	Indians account for less than 1 percent of the U.S. population today, spread mostly across the West on 314 reservations.
8_46	0.0	The differences in culture and prosperity among the Hopi, the Mohawks, the Seminoles are as varied as those among the British, the Italians, the Russians.
8_47	0.0	Contrary to conventional wisdom, gambling has reversed the fortunes of only a few tribes.
8_48	0.0	Congress' General Accounting Office estimates that 40 percent of Indian gambling revenue comes from eight of 184 tribal casinos.
8_49	0.0	The country's largest tribe, the Navajo, twice rejected gambling.
8_50	0.3076923076923077	Poverty among the Sioux on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota makes theirs the poorest county in the country.
8_51	0.07142857142857142	Less than a day's drive to the east finds Minnesota's Mille Lacs band of Chippewa awash in casino profits.
8_52	0.0	Despite those differences a new Indian movement grows that sees salvation in sovereignty and its foundations in U.S. law.
8_53	0.0	Thirty years ago, up to three dozen Indians practiced law.
8_54	0.16666666666666666	Now most estimates put that number at more than 1,000 _ still small compared with the rest of the population, but a dramatic increase.
8_55	0.08333333333333333	``Tribes are trying to come into the modern world,'' said Lawrence Baca, president-elect of the Native American Bar Association.
8_56	0.2	``Using the law is something just to get the tribes out of a situation of poverty''.
8_57	0.0	The tribes' new pragmatism also shows in more than $2 million in political donations made in the 1996 election cycle.
8_58	0.038461538461538464	Their assertiveness is seen in different ways in different places: The Mashantucket Pequots in Connecticut used their location near large eastern cities to build the country's largest casino _ Indian or otherwise _ and now can guarantee each tribal member a job worth upward of $50,000 a year.
8_59	0.08695652173913043	The success of those Pequots and a few other tribes in the gambling business has prompted competitors, most vocally developer Donald Trump, to complain that Indians hold an unfair advantage because they pay no taxes on their profits and enjoy different standards of regulation.
8_60	0.0	Neighbors to a new prison in south-central Missouri battled mightily, but unsuccessfully, to stop the $73 million project.
8_61	0.0	But the Iowa tribe of Oklahoma was able to halt construction last month.
