8_65	0.0	, has converted its failed bingo hall into a cigarette manufacturing plant and is marketing its cigarettes on reservations throughout the country.
8_66	0.2222222222222222	An Indian-made product sold on Indian land is exempt from state taxes.
8_67	0.0	Consequently, full flavor, menthol, light and ultra-light Omahas can undercut the non-tribal competition.
8_68	0.0	A U.S.
8_69	0.06666666666666667	Supreme Court case soon will decide whether eight Chippewa tribes may continue hunting and fishing free of any state regulation in Minnesota.
8_70	0.047619047619047616	While state officials worry that ruling with the tribes could lead to a plundering of Minnesota's wild game, the tribes insist they've held the right to hunt and fish at will for 150 years.
8_71	0.0	And at a time when states fight bitterly to keep out nuclear waste, the Skull Valley band of Goshutes, barely 100 strong, is inviting the country's radioactive spent fuel rods onto its small and barren reservation southwest of Salt Lake City.
8_72	0.0	Taking in the nuclear trash could create an annuity for members of the tribe.
8_73	0.0	Although Utah hasn't explicitly conceded that the tribe can legally store the waste, the governor and the Legislature have chosen to point their efforts at the transportation of radioactive material over public lands rather than challenge outright what the Goshutes can do on their reservation.
8_74	0.0	Neighbors, meantime, feel frustrated.
8_75	0.0	``It's tough fighting somebody like the Goshutes who have that authority,'' said Chip Ward of nearby Grantsville, Utah.
8_76	0.0	So often, reservations appeared all but worthless until oil or some other bonanza was discovered.
8_77	0.0	Today, sovereignty and the power to govern a patch of land is the great find.
8_78	0.0	Consider the Coeur d'Alene tribe in northern Idaho and the lake that bears its name.
8_79	0.14285714285714285	Treaties made between the tribe and federal government in 1887 and 1889 reduced the reservation's boundaries but granted the lake to the Coeur d'Alenes.
8_80	0.0	When Idaho was admitted to the union in 1890, however, it became entitled to the Constitution's promise that new states are granted all the beds, banks and waters of navigable lakes or rivers within their boundaries.
8_81	0.0	Congress didn't get around to ratifying the 1887 and 1889 treaties until 1891, a year after Idaho became a state.
8_82	0.0	To complicate things further, a presidential executive order in 1873 promised the lake to tribes, but that action never sought or gained congressional approval.
8_83	0.0	So far the Supreme Court has said that the northern two-thirds of the lake belongs to Idaho, but the tribe is still pressing a claim on the southern third.
8_84	0.0	Why does it matter?
8_85	0.0	``If the tribe owns a portion of the lake, you could have competing water quality standards, disputes over fishing seasons, questions over easements for docks and power lines,'' said Clive Strong of the Idaho attorney general's office.
8_86	0.0	Likewise, logs floated to sawmills would need to pass through tribe-controlled water.
8_87	0.0	The tribe, meantime, jealously defends the exercise of sovereignty it credits for turning around the prospects of its members in recent years.
8_88	0.06666666666666667	Five years ago, before the Coeur d'Alene tribe opened a casino, unemployment among its 1,600 members was nearly 65 percent.
8_89	0.0	Now, despite legal challenges from attorneys general in Missouri and other states, the tribe is operating an on-line worldwide lottery at http:
9_0	0.0	PEACH SPRINGS, Ariz.
9_1	0.08333333333333333	(AP) - When American Indians began embracing gambling as an economic development tool in the 1990s, the Hualapai tribe in northern Arizona moved quickly to open a casino at its Grand Canyon West tourist site.
9_2	0.26666666666666666	Tribal leaders figured that slot machines would provide new revenue for the tribe's 1,200 members, many of whom have lived in poverty for years.
9_3	0.0	But they forgot that most of the 100,000 visitors to Grand Canyon West each year come directly from Las Vegas.
9_4	0.0	''Those people weren't coming to a casino,'' said Louise Benson, tribal chairman.
9_5	0.0	''They were coming to see the Grand Canyon''.
9_6	0.2	Less than a year after opening the casino, the Hualapai shut it down.
9_7	0.0	Instead of providing an economic boom to tribal members, it left them $1 million in debt.
9_8	0.0	''There were high hopes for that casino, but the reality of it was that we were too isolated,'' said Alex Cabillo, the tribe's director of public works.
9_9	0.0	The Hualapai tribe is one of only two whose casinos failed during the Indian gambling boom of the past decade, when revenues exploded from $100 million in 1988 to $8.26 billion in 1998.
9_10	0.043478260869565216	But an Associated Press computer analysis of federal unemployment, poverty and public assistance records indicates that the vast majority of American Indians, like the Hualapai, have not realized the early ''high hopes'' of the casino boom.
