16_0	0.0	NEAH BAY, Wash.
16_1	0.0	_ Micah McCarty rises with the sun and slips into the chilly waters of Waatch River, just upstream from the untamed edge of the Pacific Northwest.
16_2	0.0	With each stroke, he mimics the movement of the whale he hopes to slay this fall with a hand-carved wooden harpoon.
16_3	0.0	And he prays that the gray whale will be ``a kind brother or sister''.
16_4	0.0	McCarty is preparing himself for the Makah tribe's first whale hunt in more than seven decades.
16_5	0.0	He hopes it will renew the Olympic Peninsula tribe's spirit and traditions.
16_6	0.0	Opponents call the hunt butchery, saying it has no place in a modern world where whales are protected by international law.
16_7	0.0	McCarty wants to be the ``chosen one''.
16_8	0.0	The harpooner will stand in a dugout canoe, steady himself against 10-foot Pacific swells, heft the barbed lance, take aim and plunge it into the back of a 38-foot leviathan.
16_9	0.0	The kill will be a sacred moment for the Makah, honoring the great whale.
16_10	0.0	But the eight men in the canoe _ keepers of a ritual dating back at least 100 generations _ will be encircled by an armada of outraged animal rights activists, a swarm of international media and a thin phalanx of security.
16_11	0.0	The hunt's notoriety stems from a controversial decision by the International Whaling Commission that granted the Makah the right to kill up to 20 whales through 2002.
16_12	0.0	Animal rights activists fear the hunt will spark a wholesale return to commercial whaling, presently banned by the commission.
16_13	0.0	But as the 27-year-old McCarty runs barefoot along Hobuck Beach, he does not think about the global forces aligned against the 1,800 people living in his fishing village.
16_14	0.0	Instead, he meditates and prays to make his spirit pure to receive the whale, ``an honored guest of the village''.
16_15	0.0	He anchors his feet in the sand of the beach and heaves hunks of driftwood in hopes of being chosen the harpooner.
16_16	0.0	McCarty is one of 16 men selected by Makah families to compete for eight spots on the first tribal whaling crew since the 1920s.
16_17	0.0	He feels the excitement building on this 44-square-mile reservation of heavily logged rain forest and spectacular wilderness beach located at the extreme northwest tip of the contiguous United States.
16_18	0.0	The return to whaling will be a sort of homecoming for the Makah, whose real name _ which cannot be written in English _ means ``people who live by the rocks and the seagulls''.
16_19	0.0	McCarty comes from a long line of whalers.
16_20	0.0	His grandfather and great-grandfather participated in the last hunts before whaling was suspended, because gray whales had been stalked almost to extinction by non-Indian whalers.
16_21	0.0	McCarty's father, John, until recently was executive director of the tribe's whaling commission.
16_22	0.0	After graduating from high school in Olympia, Micah McCarty came home to Neah Bay and immersed himself in the maritime life, working with his father as a commercial fisherman.
16_23	0.0	``It became a passionate connection with the waters my ancestors plied,'' McCarty said.
16_24	0.0	Like the Makah whalers before him, McCarty prepares by purifying himself in frigid streams such as the Waatch River.
16_25	0.0	``We look upon the water as its own being,'' he said.
16_26	0.0	While bathing, McCarty said he ``thinks about the whale moving gracefully through the water, and I swim as gracefully as I can.
16_27	0.0	... And I pray that our whale crew will be one mind, one body, one spirit''.
16_28	0.0	Historically, secrecy guarded every aspect of Makah whaling from the hunt to the communal butchering and feasting, according to anthropological texts.
16_29	0.0	Tribal members today remain guarded about saying too much about the hunt to outsiders.
16_30	0.0	``It is usually taboo to even talk about,'' McCarty said.
16_31	0.0	``Usually, you just prepare yourself and go whaling''.
16_32	0.0	McCarty, like his father and the rest of the tribe, is acutely aware of the international controversy surrounding this fall's hunt.
16_33	0.0	``In this day and age, it's important to say something about it,'' McCarty said.
16_34	0.0	To illustrate that whaling still defines the fabric of Makah life, McCarty shares a few words from sacred whaling songs that have been passed down from generation to generation and are still sung today.
16_35	0.0	One song says ``my canoe travels with killer whales as an escort,'' and another says ``my canoe travels with lightning''.
16_36	0.0	``I might get in trouble for telling you that, but it's not a direct translation,'' he said.
16_37	0.0	McCarty said he has wanted to hunt whales for a long time, long before they became news to the outside world.
16_38	0.0	An accomplished carver whose art is sold at a shop called Tribes in Fremont, McCarty frequently creates masks that call upon spirits related to whaling and the sea.
16_39	0.0	``As I learned about our oral history, some of the songs and dances we do, my artwork took on more meaning about who we are and where we come from''.
16_40	0.0	The other whalers said McCarty and crew member Darrell Markishtum frequently lead them in ancient paddle songs as they practice stealth and speed in the red and black dugout canoe called the Hummingbird.
16_41	0.0	``The songs keep your mind off the pain'' of paddling for hours, said Don Swan, a powerfully built man who, like McCarty, would like to be the ``chosen one'' to heft the harpoon.
16_42	0.4	Neah Bay, like many other Native American communities, is struggling with unemployment rates often exceeding 50 percent, deep poverty and the problems of crime, drug and alcohol abuse and domestic violence.
16_43	0.0	McCarty hopes the return to whaling will provide inspiration and a new focus for the community.
16_44	0.0	``It is a sacred way of life that sets an honorable example,'' he said.
16_45	0.0	Whaling ``involves so much concentration, so much preparation, that anyone who was involved in that lifestyle (substance abuse or violence) would have to drop it''.
