24_0	0.0	MACY, Neb.
24_1	0.0	_ There was no Christmas vacation this year at the Omaha Nation Public School, and no spring break either.
24_2	0.0	Instead, the superintendent, Todd Chessmore, decided to front load the school calendar so classes would end a few weeks early, the first week of May.
24_3	0.0	This was his attempt to stem a chronically high truancy rate that gets worse in the spring, when warmer weather and the end of the high school basketball season dampen students' interest in school.
24_4	0.0	It was not entirely successful.
24_5	0.0	In the math class taught by Chessmore, for example, only five of the 36 registered students were showing up by mid-April.
24_6	0.0	Even in a country used to stories about struggling public schools, many of those in Indian country stand out.
24_7	0.0	Last year, the average student at the Omaha Nation Public School scored in the 15th percentile on national standardized tests, and almost half scored below the 10th percentile.
24_8	0.0	Fewer than half the students in grades three through 12 came to take the test, Chessmore said.
24_9	0.0	And while this year's graduating class of nine is bigger than those of a few years ago, it represents only a third of the 27 students enrolled in that class in ninth grade.
24_10	0.0	The obstacles the Omaha Nation school wrestles with are echoed in Indian schools around the country.
24_11	0.1	On average, 36 percent to 51 percent of Indian students drop out of high school, according to the American Indian College Fund, the largest dropout rate of any ethnic group.
24_12	0.0	Only about 17 percent of high school graduates go to college, and most do not finish.
24_13	0.391304347826087	``We got the worst of everything, the lowest test scores, lowest rate of reading books, the highest dropout rate, the lowest rate of entering college,'' said Dean Chavers, director of the Native American Scholarship Fund.
24_14	0.0	``Whatever test you're looking at, Indian kids in high school typically score at the 15th or 20th percentile.
24_15	0.0	The reading of those kids is absolutely nonexistent.
24_16	0.0	Our Indian kids are leaving high school now with Algebra 1 _ no geometry, no trig _ and people wonder why they're failing out of college''.
24_17	0.14285714285714285	Frustrated by years of distressing results, schools and groups like the National Indian Education Association have begun pressing states and the federal government for more money for academics and crumbling buildings, programs to train Indian teachers, and support for parents whose poverty, substance abuse or unemployment leave them unmotivated or unable to help their children stay in school and achieve.
24_18	0.05263157894736842	The effort reflects the Indians' increasing ability to assert itself, as Indian leaders have gained political and legal savvy and a degree of economic empowerment through reservation casinos.
24_19	0.0	But it also reflects the critical state of Indian education.
24_20	0.1	Some reservation schools have done well and others, including the Omaha Nation school, have improved from a few years ago.
24_21	0.0	But many are dealing with a cycle of low expectations from non-Indian teachers, a generation of poorly educated parents, broken and overwhelmed families, a society historically suspicious of government-run schools and a culture that may not always see the relationship between being academically rigorous and being successful on the reservation.
24_22	0.0	These difficulties only compound the isolation and poverty of reservation life.
24_23	0.0	``I worry about the future of the tribe,'' said Denine Parker, an Omaha tribe member who teaches art at the school in Macy, where 60 percent of the 3,400 tribe members are unemployed.
